<F P=100> AUSTRALIASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reveals Stance on Rwanda Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reveals Stance on Rwanda Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Evans Concerned at Size of UN Force </H4>

<F P=102> BK1805070294 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1805070294 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Australia has expressed reservations about the size 
of the new United Nations mission for Rwanda. Foreign Minister 
Gareth Evans says Australia will not offer troops to the force 
until there is a proper mandate and enough soldiers to do the 
job. 
  Senator Evans said it was unclear whether the Rwanda 
operation could be done with the 5,500 troops proposed by the 
United Nations, and he said there was some distance to go before 
the Security Council decision could be translated into something 
that was workable in Rwanda. 
  The international medical aid organization Doctors Without 
Borders says the deployment of United Nations troops to Rwanda 
may come too late to help save thousands of Rwandan civilians. 
It urged the Security Council to speed up deployment, saying 
that there are hundreds of people facing systematic slaughter. 

</TEXT>

