<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Says Economy Likely To Recover in Fall </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Says Economy Likely To Recover in Fall </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105061094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 21 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2105061094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 21 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata touched on the outlook 
for economic recovery at a 20 May House of Councilors Budget 
Committee session and said: "We would like to watch the 
economic situation carefully while hoping to see a certain, 
clear sign of recovery this fall or after." Prime Minister Hata 
indicated that the economy would be on the track for 
full-fledged recovery as early as fall. In reply to Diet 
interpellations, government officials have so far reiterated 
that "the economy is expected to be on track for full-fledged 
recovery by the end of fiscal 1994" (as stated by Yoshio 
Terasawa, director general of the Economic Planning Agency). 
Prime Minister Hata's remark was the first government view that 
this fall is the goal of full-fledged economic recovery. 
  Touching on concrete measures to stimulate the sluggish 
economy, Prime Minister Hata also stated that "it is important 
to deal with" the execution of the budget "while studying the 
possibility of front-loading spending" after the Diet passes the 
budget. Moreover, he stressed the need for promotion of 
deregulation and the stability in the yen's exchange rate to the 
dollar. 

</TEXT>

