<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Councilor Expects IAEA Delegation Entry Approval </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Councilor Expects IAEA Delegation Entry Approval </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205052094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2205052094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yukihiko Machida; from MAINICHI SHIMBUN 21 May Evening </F>
Edition] 
  [Text] Vienna, 20 May -- On 20 May, a councilor at the DPRK 
(North Korean) Embassy in Vienna commented on a 19 May proposal 
by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to send a 
delegation to North Korea in connection with the issue of 
inspecting fuel rods at a nuclear reactor in Yongbyon. The 
councilor said: "We have not yet received a reply from 
Pyongyang. However, I expect that a positive answer to the IAEA 
proposal will come." He thus disclosed North Korea's intention 
to accept the IAEA proposal. In reply to MAINICHI SHIMBUN 
questions, the councilor stressed North Korea's positive 
attitude toward accepting the IAEA delegation, and clearly said: 
"The scale of the delegation is an issue that should be decided 
by the IAEA. We have no intention of making any requests on 
that." 
  Moreover, in discussing an IAEA request for the picking of 
sample fuel rods, the councilor said: "It is clear that we are 
ready to provide basic materials to the IAEA to comply with 
safeguard obligations by accepting nuclear inspections." Thus, 
he hinted at an intention to take a flexible stance on picking 
of the samples. 
  However, regarding a 19 May IAEA request that the exchange 
of 
fuel rods be postponed, the councilor said: "I do not think 
(North Korea) will accept it." North Korea is expected to 
submit an official reply to the IAEA in a day or two. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

