<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan Called `Hypocrite' for Plutonium `Concealment' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan Called `Hypocrite' for Plutonium `Concealment' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2105111294 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1056 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2105111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Hypocrite Unmasked" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 21 (KCNA) -- The recently exposed 
concealment of 70 kilograms of undeclared pure-powder plutonium 
in Japan has brought into a glaring light the true color of 
Japan as a hypocrite trying to deliberately fool the world, 
while producing and stockpiling a large quantity of plutonium, 
says MINJU CHOSON today. 
  The analyst continues: 
  The Japanese reactionaries, captive to the desire to convert 
Japan into a nuclear power, have promoted the introduction, 
deployment and stockpile of nuclear weapons behind the spurious 
curtain of "three non-nuclear principles." They are now stepping 
up nuclear armament, raising a hue and cry over "the nuclear 
suspicion" against the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and 
its "nuclear issue." 
  It was the first time that undeclared plutonium was 
discovered in Japan. But nobody can tell how much plutonium is 
concealed in Japan. 
  The recently exposed concealment of plutonium makes us cast 
doubt on the impartiality of the International Atomic Energy 
Agency in its inspections. 
  The IAEA arbitrarily branded the fledgling peaceful nuclear 
activities of such small countries as ours as "nuclear 
development", while conniving at the dangerous nuclear 
activities of Japan. This is obviously an undisguised 
application of a double standard. 
  The Japanese reactionaries must stop the despicable nuclear 
gamble, open to the public the quantity of the concealed 
plutonium and behave themselves. 
  The United States and the IAEA would be well advised to pay 
due attention to Japan's nuclear armament, adhering to the 
principle of impartiality. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

