<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Urges Japan To Give Up Nuclear Armament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Urges Japan To Give Up Nuclear Armament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2205085194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0823 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2205085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Japan in the Dock as Nuclear Criminal" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 22 (KCNA) -- The recent discovery of 
a large quantity of nuclear material in Japan evidently shows 
once again that her design for nuclear armament has gone to 
extremes, notes NODONG SINMUN in a commentary today. 
  The news analyst says: 
  The Japanese reactionaries invented a "nuclear suspicion" 
about the DPRK and have acted as if they were a "nuclear judge". 
Expressing dissatisfaction at the adequate inspections of the 
DPRK, they have resorted to pressure demanding a "special 
inspection", an "additional inspection" and kicked up a row in 
an effort to make the United Nations impose "sanctions" on the 
DPRK. 
  They even prepared an "emergency legislative arrangement" 
for 
a dispatch of their "self-defence forces" to the Korean 
peninsula, talking about "response" in case the UN should adopt 
a resolution on "sanctions". 
  The recent discovery of plutonium kept in hiding made it all 
the clearer why Japan has been so hell bent on false propaganda 
about "nuclear suspicion" on the DPRK. 
  It is, indeed, a mean intrigue that Japan has engaged in 
hostile acts against the DPRK, spreading a groundless lie to 
brand it as a nuclear criminal, while keeping a large quantity 
of nuclear weapons- grade material in hiding. 
  Japan, a nuclear criminal, has tried desperately to place 
others in the dock as a nuclear criminal, but she herself has to 
sit in it. 
  Japan must stop at once her intrigues to do harm to the DPRK 
over the "nuclear issue", clearly declare to the international 
community the total amount of plutonium concealed nationwide and 
give up her nuclear armament. 

</TEXT>

