<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Groups Support DPRK Peace Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Groups Support DPRK Peace Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2005151194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1503 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2005151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 20 (KCNA) -- A statement of the DPRK 
Foreign Ministry on establishing a new peace arrangement was 
fully supported by organizations and public figures of different 
countries. 
  The Finland-Korea Association and the Finish Solidarity 
Committee for Korea's reunification in a letter to the United 
States administration adopted at a joint meeting, called on it 
to accept the proposal to establish a new peace arrangement on 
the Korean peninsula at an early date and show in action its 
efforts to ensure peace. 
  The Secretariat of the Communist Party of Finland (Unity) in 
a statement said that the present situation requires the 
replacement of the Armistice Agreement with a peace agreement 
immediately and establishment of a new peace arrangement on the 
Korean peninsula, and expressed the hope that the Korean problem 
would be solved in a peaceful way in any case. 
  Negotiations to replace the Armistice Agreement with a peace 
agreement and establish a new peace arrangement for creditably 
guaranteeing a durable peace and security of the Korean 
peninsula will open a vista to remove the hostile relations 
between the DPRK and the United States and resolve the nuclear 
issue and other complicated problems in this area, the Popular 
Party for Democracy and Development of Ghana said in a statement. 
  Madhav Kumar Nepal, general secretary of the Central 
Committee of the Nepal Communist Party (United 
Marxism-Leninism), pointed out in a statement that they support 
the proposal for a peace agreement, and expressed the belief 
that it would help solve the dispute and achieve peace and 
stability on the Korean peninsula. 
  We call upon the peace-loving people of the world to 
actively 
in denouncing the U.S. hostile policy toward Korea join said 
Dilip Barua, general secretary of the Communist Party of 
Bangladesh (Marxist-Leninist). 
  He positively supported the just proposal of the DPRK to 
establish a new peace arrangement which will replace the 
Armistice Agreement. 

</TEXT>

