<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calcium Silicate Brick Houses Built for Families </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calcium Silicate Brick Houses Built for Families </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2105114094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1030 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2105114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 21 (KCNA) -- Many calcium silicate 
brick houses are under construction in Korea. 
  In recent years alone, more than 400 rural villages of 
calcium silicate brick houses have made their appearance in some 
120 cities, counties and ri. Dwelling houses for more than 
35,000 families have been built in these villages. 
  Houses of this type are very convenient for rural life. Each 
flat has a floor space of 90 to 120 square metres. 
  Cooking and heating are done by methane gas at the dwelling 
houses in many rural villages including Yongjin-ri, Kaechon City. 
  The construction of calcium silicate brick houses in Korea 
began at the end of the 1980s. 
  The dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il, always paying deep 
attention to the betterment of the people's living, saw to it 
that calcium silicate brick production bases were built in Anju, 
Pihyon and Hamhung to more satisfactorily meet the increasing 
needs for dwelling houses, and wisely led their construction. 
Thus, the construction of calcium silicate brick factories with 
a total production capacity of 1,000 million bricks was 
completed successfully in two years. 
  Comrade Kim Chong-il saw designs of calcium silicate brick 
houses in May, 1986. Saying it was the wish of the great leader 
President Kim Il-song and his own determination to enable all 
the people to live in such good houses, he stressed that such 
houses should be built on an extensive basis in Pyongyang and 
local cities and rural villages. 
  As a result, peculiar dwelling houses have appeared in 
Pyongyang and provincial, city and county seats and rural 
villages. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53666 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas099_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on U.S.-Japan Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on U.S.-Japan Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Exploratory Talks' Described </H4>

<F P=102> OW2105020894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0148 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105020894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Antonio Kamiya] </F>
  [Text] Washington, May 20 KYODO -- Japanese and U.S. 
officials met for the second straight day Friday [20 May] but 
still came up short of a deal to jump-start stalled trade talks 
on ways to increase foreign access to key Japanese markets. 
  The two sides agreed to make another try Saturday. 
  "There has been progress in mutual understanding," said a 
Japanese official involved in the negotiations. 
  The negotiations, which lasted five hours Friday, were aimed 
at breaking a three-month deadlock in the so-called "framework" 
talks that has badly strained bilateral trade ties. 
  While officials declined to comment on what transpired 
across 
the negotiating table, U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
underscored the importance of the meeting by personally 
attending part of the "exploratory talks" between subcabinet 
officials. 
  Representing the Japanese team were Vice Minister of 
International Trade and Industry Sozaburo Okamatsu and Deputy 
Foreign Minister Sadayuki Hayashi. 
  The U.S. delegation consisted of two principal Japan trade 
negotiators, Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Charlene 
Barshefsky and Presidential National Economic Council Deputy 
Director Bowman Cutter. 
  Like their Japanese counterparts, U.S. officials involved in 
the talks were equally tight-lipped. 
  "You know I can't talk," said a U.S. official when asked for 
comment. 
  Cutter, however, sought to project an air of conviviality 
after emerging from the morning session. 
  "We had a good and cordial conversation, and we will meet 
again," Cutter told reporters. 
  The trade talks, which are closely watched on financial 
markets as a barometer in the state of relationship between the 
world's two largest economies, ruptured in February at a meeting 
in Washington between President Bill Clinton and then Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, who succeeded Hosokawa in late 
April, and Clinton agreed last week to work out a common "basis" 
for restarting the framework talks before they meet at the group 
seven summit in Naples in early July. 
  One major sticking point in the framework talks -- and the 
primary cause for the rupture of the negotiations at the Feb. 11 
U.S.-Japan summit -- is the idea of setting "objective criteria" 
to measure imports to Japan. 
  In what is known as a "results-oriented" approach, the U.S. 
has insisted on using "numerical indicators" to ensure that a 
trade agreement with Japan translates into increased foreign 
sales in the Japanese market. 
  Tokyo has vehemently objected to the idea, saying it amounts 
to government-managed trade. 
  Among the industry sectors covered under the "framework" 
accord are Japanese Government procurement for medical and 
telecommunications products, trade in autos and auto parts and 
the Japanese insurance market. 
  The U.S. wants Japan to open its market wider to foreign 
goods and stimulate domestic demand in order to reduce its vast, 
and growing, trade surplus. 
  The U.S.-Japan trade imbalance was underscored by fresh U.S. 
Government data Thursday that showed the U.S. trade deficit with 
Japan jumped 25 percent in March to 5.80 billion dollars. 
  The U.S. trade gap with Japan came to 15.04 billion dollars 
in the first three months of this year, well ahead of the 
comparable period last year which stood at 13.3 billion dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

