<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on U.S.-Japan Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on U.S.-Japan Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Both Sides Seek Talks Resumption </H4>

<F P=102> OW2305095094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0933 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
both want to agree during ongoing informal talks in Washington 
to resume the stalled bilateral trade framework talks, Vice 
Foreign Minister Kunihiko Saito said Monday [23 May]. 
  Saito told a news conference it is clear the two sides want 
to reach agreement on the resumption during the unofficial vice- 
ministerial talks to be held again Monday and that he hopes 
Tokyo and Washington would make efforts to achieve that. 
  Japan and the U.S. have held three rounds of exploratory 
talks since last week to weigh terms and conditions for resuming 
the negotiations under the so-called "framework" agreement 
concluded last July. 
  The trade talks, which are aimed at widening foreign access 
to the Japanese market and paring down Japan's vast trade 
surplus, broke down in February after Tokyo rejected 
Washington-proposed yardsticks to gauge progress in Japanese 
imports. 
  Saito also said a visit to the U.S. by Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa is a possibility depending on the outcome of Monday's 
unofficial talks. 
  Kakizawa has repeatedly expressed his intention to visit the 
U.S. 
  Saito said the government will consider what steps should be 
taken after the ongoing talks end. 

</TEXT>

