<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Joins UN Children's Rights Convention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Joins UN Children's Rights Convention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205072694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0655 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205072694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 22 KYODO -- Japan on Sunday [22 May] 
became a party to the United Nations Convention on the Rights of 
the Child. 
  The Foreign Ministry sent ratification documents to the 
world 
body last month and Japan's participation in the convention came 
into force on Sunday. 
  The convention, which came into force in September 1990, 
addresses the individual rights of children and sets universally 
accepted standards for their protection. 
  Japan is the 158th country to join the child protection 
treaty. 
  Some Japanese have criticized the government for defending a 
part of the country's civil code which they say violates the 
convention by discriminating against and stigmatizing 
illegitimate children. 
  Under the code an illegitimate child's inheritance is set at 
half that of a legitimate child. 
  Also, legitimate children in the family registration system 
are listed in such manner as "eldest son" or "youngest 
daughter," while illegitimate children are listed only as "male" 
or "female." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

