<H3> <TI>   Assistance Planned for South Korean Small Firms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assistance Planned for South Korean Small Firms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105064394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0613 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 21 KYODO -- Japan and South Korea will 
discuss in Tokyo next Thursday [26 May] ways to promote 
bilateral industrial cooperation for small South Korean 
companies, Japanese Trade Ministry officials said Saturday. 
  Japanese International Trade and Industry Minister [MITI] 
Eijiro Hata and his South Korean counterpart, Kim Chul-su, will 
meet to devise a joint program to foster small companies in 
South Korea, the officials said. 
  The program is expected to call for dispatch of Japanese 
experts to South Korea, Japanese companies' acceptance of South 
Korean trainees and promotion of Japanese investment in South 
Korea. 
  During the one-day meeting, both parties will also select 
South Korean companies to serve as models under the industrial 
cooperation program, the officials said. 
  An investment delegation representing 80 blue-chip companies 
in South Korea will accompany Kim. 
  The delegation will seek stepped-up Japanese investment in 
its country in Tokyo, Osaka and Kitakyushu, the MITI officials 
said. 

</TEXT>

