<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agency Chief Cautious on Russian Fishing Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agency Chief Cautious on Russian Fishing Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205082994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0805 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nemuro, Hokkaido, May 22 KYODO -- State Minister 
Moriyoshi Sato on Sunday [22 May] opposed a Russian proposal 
that Japanese fishing ships be allowed to operate in waters off 
four Russian-occupied islands claimed by Japan provided they pay 
fishing charges. 
  "As the Northern Territories are Japan's inherent territory 
(Japan) should not authorize any Russian intervention, including 
joint fishing ventures," said Sato, who is director general of 
the Hokkaido and Okinawa Development Agencies. 
  Nikolai Pokidin, head of the South Kurils Administration, 
earlier this year proposed that both sides strike a commercial 
deal on fishing in the area. 
  But Tokyo has rejected the proposal out of concern that such 
a step could be taken as an indirect recognition of Russian 
sovereignty over the territory. 
  Sato visited the city of Nemuro on the eastern tip of 
Hokkaido to view the Russian-held islands from Nosappu Point. 
  Japan has long demanded the return of Kunashiri, Etorofu, 
Shikotan and the Habomai group of islets, known in Japan as the 
Northern Territories, which were seized by the Soviet Union at 
the end of World War II. 
  Russia has voiced protest over hundreds of border violations 
by Japanese fishing boats in the area over the last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

