<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 22 KYODO -- New party Sakigake leader 
Masayoshi Takemura left Tokyo on Sunday [22 May] on a weeklong 
visit to the United States for talks with government and 
congressional leaders on economic and trade issues, and North 
Korea's suspected nuclear weapons program. 
  Sakigake officials said Takemura, 59, will also talk with 
U.S. officials about Japan's bid to become a permanent member of 
the U.N. Security Council. 
  He will address the Asia-Pacific Center in San Francisco on 
Thursday before returning home Saturday, they said. 
  Sakigake, set up by a splinter group of 15 Liberal 
Democratic 
Party (LDP) legislators, quit the ruling coalition in April 
along with the Social Democratic Party (SDP), leaving the 
cabinet of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata a minority government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

