<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to Utility Rate Freeze </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to Utility Rate Freeze </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MITI Urges Utilities To Cooperate </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005141094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1322 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 20 KYODO -- The Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) will urge Japanese 
electric power and major city gas suppliers to avoid raising 
their rates after October, ministry officials said Friday [20 
May]. The power and gas utilities in November 1993 implemented 
a temporary cut in their rates, valid until September, to pass 
on the benefits of the yen's appreciation against the dollar to 
consumers. The stronger yen has reduced crude oil import costs 
for the utilities. 
  The rate cut has lowered the monthly electric power bill for 
the standard household by 100 yen and the city gas cost by 138 
yen. 
  The government said Wednesday it will freeze until the end 
of 
the year proposed hikes in public service charges, including 
power and gas rates, public transportation fares and telephone 
rates. But Hiroshi Watanabe, chairman of the Japan Gas 
Association, told reporters Thursday that member companies plan 
to end the rate cut after October. 

</TEXT>

