BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- The government's move to 
freeze a planned hike in various public services charges will 
give a psychological boost to consumers made cautious by the 
recession, a senior government official said Monday [23 May]. 
  Tsutomu Tanaka, vice minister of the Economic Planning 
Agency, told a press conference that the freeze also will bring 
about other favorable effects on the economy, by prompting 
public utility companies which had planned to raise their 
charges to undergo further restructuring measures. 
  The government announced last Wednesday that public fees 
would not be increased this year, including those for telephone 
services, taxis and national highway tolls. 
  Tanaka said he had been informed of the announcement the 
night before. 
  Asked why Jiro Saito, vice finance minister, was not 
informed 
of the announcement until the next day, as he later complained, 
Tanaka said that he himself was only informed apparently because 
he was due to leave Japan on Wednesday for an Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development meeting in Paris. 

</TEXT>

