<H3> <TI>   SDPJ's Murayama Urges Hata Cabinet To Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ's Murayama Urges Hata Cabinet To Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205075294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0735 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205075294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fukushima, May 22 KYODO -- The leader of the 
country's second largest opposition party renewed its call for 
the minority cabinet of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata to resign 
immediately after the state budget passes the Diet. 
  Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the Social Democratic Party 
[of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ], said there is no difference of opinion 
between him and the party's No. 2 man, Wataru Kubo, the SDPJ 
secretary general. 
  On Saturday in China, Kubo said that the Hata cabinet should 
resign en masse soon after the Diet approves the fiscal 1994 
budget bills and before the opposition camp submits a 
no-confidence motion. 
  Murayama, delivering a speech in the city of Fukushima, some 
270 kilometers northeast of Tokyo, said talks can be launched 
among various political parties to restructure the coalition 
government. 
  The present coalition is mainly formed by Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party], Komeito, and the Japan New Party. The SDPJ, 
which was the No. 1 component of the previous cabinet led by 
Morihiro Hosokawa, quit the coalition late last month in protest 
against the abrupt formation of a large parliamentary group 
excluding the SDPJ. 
  Meanwhile, the SDPJ chairman also said a dissolution of the 
House of Representatives for a snap general election might be 
inevitable in the event of political turmoil. "There may be no 
other way but to seek the judgment of voters," he said. 

</TEXT>

