<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 21 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
hinted Saturday [21 May] he may consider an opposition proposal 
that his minority cabinet resign immediately after the state 
budget passes the Diet. 
  "It is one idea," Hata said. 
  Hata told reporters that he will meet or talk over the 
telephone with Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan], the 
second largest opposition party, who made the suggestion earlier 
in the day. 
  Meanwhile, chief cabinet secretary Hiroshi Kumagai told 
reporters that the cabinet will take Kubo's proposal seriously. 
  Kubo, in a meeting in China with Japanese reporters 
traveling 
with him, said that the Hata cabinet should resign en masse soon 
after the fiscal 1994 budget bills are approved by the Diet, and 
before the opposition camp submits a no-confidence motion. 
  Kubo said the SDP may seek a no-confidence vote if Hata 
refuses to step down. The possibility of an SDP no-confidence 
motion would be "very high" if the Hata cabinet does not resign 
en masse, he said. 

