<DOCNO> FBIS4-53691 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas099_a_94027" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Rejects Demand To Disband Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Rejects Demand To Disband Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305122694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1211 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
on Monday [23 May] spurned an opposition demand to disband his 
minority cabinet upon parliamentary passage of the fiscal 1994 
state budget. 
  "There should not be a standoff between the ruling coalition 
and the opposition camp," Hata told the House of Representatives 
Budget Committee. He added that his administration, "is 
sincerely seeking to implement the common policy agreement." 
  The premier was responding to a query by Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) legislator Shun Oide. 
  The SDP, which was the No. 1 component of the previous 
cabinet led by Morihiro Hosokawa, stormed out of the coalition 
late last month in protest against the abrupt formation of a 
large parliamentary group excluding the SDP. The SDP's move 
forced Hata to form Japan's first minority government in 39 
years. 
  SDP Secretary General Wataru Kubo demanded Saturday that the 
Hata Cabinet should resign en masse after the fiscal 1994 budget 
bills are approved by the Diet, and before the opposition camp 
submits a motion of no-confidence. 
  Kubo also hinted that the SDP, which holds the deciding vote 
in the Diet, may move to make a reconciliation with its former 
coalition partners if Hata bows out. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama said Sunday there is no 
difference of opinion between him and Kubo. Murayama said a 
dissolution of the lower house for a snap general election might 
be inevitable in the event of political turmoil. 
  Yohei Kono, president of the largest opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party, said Monday he agrees with the SDP on the 
issue. 
  Oide urged Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa to withdraw his 
recently published comments that Japan needs to apply a more 
flexible interpretation to the Constitution in order to defend 
itself in the face of a "possible threat from North Korea's 
missiles and the buildup of China's naval forces." 
  Oide took issue with a statement of Kakizawa's published in 
a 
book that carried proposals from 200 intellectuals and 
politicians. 
  Kakizawa rejected Oide's demand to renege his conviction 
about Japan's defense policy, while promising to live up to the 
Hata administration's vow not to amend interpretation of the 
Constitution. 
  Hata rejected Oide's demand that Kakizawa be dismissed as 
foreign minister to take account for his remark. 
  Hata renewed a pledge Monday to seek the passage of the 
overdue fiscal 1994 state budget by the end of the current Diet 
session as discussions on the budget finally started. 
  Hata said,"I really hope the budget passes in the current 
Diet session by any means. I will make most sincere efforts for 
that." The Diet session is scheduled to end June 29. 
  "I feel great responsibility. I regret the delay," Hata 
said. Nearly 80 days have passed since the government submitted 
the budget to the Diet for deliberations. 
  He was responding to questions by an LDP legislator Takashi 
Fukaya. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai denied he is seeking 
an extension of the term of the current Diet session to ensure 
the passage of the budget. 
  Hata declined to talk about an extension of the Diet 
session, 
saying it is a matter that should be decided by the Diet. 
  Kumagai also promised a formal report on the recent "sexist" 
remarks by Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito and top 
policy strategist in the ruling coalition. 
  Kumagai said he will directly ask Ozawa what he really meant 
by the remarks and will brief the committee session. 
  He was referring to Ozawa's remarks last month which 
defended 
the move among some coalition partners to create a new Diet bloc 
without the SDP. 
  Comparing the convergence of various political parties to an 
extramarital affair, Ozawa reportedly told reporters, "it 
doesn't matter which women you may sleep with." 
  Kumagai said the remarks are "not appropriate if they were 
really made." 

</TEXT>

