<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Revises `Universal Security' Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Revises `Universal Security' Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105005694 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1000 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2105005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News 7" </F>
program] 
  [Text] In the upper house Budget Committee session today, 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata explained the coalition's uniform 
definition of the expression Fuhenteki Anzen Hosho [Universal 
Security] -- the expression used in describing Japan's concept 
of security in the coalition parties' policy agreements. Hata 
said the coalition's uniform view is that this expression refers 
only to the general framework of peace and security provided by 
the United Nations. 
  The collective security in the UN Charter means a 
cooperative 
act by the international community to restore peace if peace is 
threatened or an act of aggression takes place. The charter 
also talks about possible specific actions, including military 
operations. But Prime Minister Hata said the concept of 
universal security refers to the general framework accepted by 
the international community on maintaining peace and security 
under the United Nations. He said this term is different from 
collective security, but did not clarify whether this term has a 
military connotation. 
  The coalition partners have been said to have different 
views 
on the question of whether the term [universal security] 
included the possibility of military action. Prime Minister 
Hata had earlier told the lower house Budget Committee that the 
words -- universal security and collective security -- have 
roughly the same meaning. 
  Today's announcement that the two terms do have different 
meanings amounts to an amendment to Hata's earlier statement. 
Observers said this is an attempt by the coalition partners to 
avoid giving the impression that since the two terms are said to 
be the same thing, the Japanese Government may be willing to 
take part in UN military operations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

