<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sakigake's Takemura Criticizes Strategist Ozawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sakigake's Takemura Criticizes Strategist Ozawa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105103494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1026 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Utsunomiya, May 21 KYODO -- The leader of new party 
Sakigake [Harbinger], a 15-member opposition group in the House 
of Representatives, criticized chief coalition strategist Ichiro 
Ozawa on Saturday [21 May] of trying to turn the country into a 
major military power. 
  In a speech in Utsunomiya, some 110 kilometers north of 
Tokyo, Masayoshi Takemura said he was opposed to Ozawa's 
argument for turning Japan into what Ozawa calls an "ordinary 
country." 
  When Ozawa says "ordinary country," he means one which owns 
a 
military commensurate with its economic capability and assumes 
responsibility jointly with the United States for troubles in 
the world, Takemura said. 
  Takemura, who served as chief cabinet secretary until late 
last month in the cabinet of former Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, said his party will never follow the path toward such 
a military power. 
  Takemura said Japan should make international contributions 
in such nonmilitary fields as environmental protection, 
north-south issues, aids and narcotics. 
  Ozawa is regarded as the de facto leader of the ruling 
coalition's core party Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], which is 
nominally headed by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata. 
  While Ozawa calls for changing Japan into an "ordinary 
country," Takemura has proposed the nation be a "small but 
twinkling country." 
  Many political analysts say differences between Ozawa and 
Takemura represented the underlying cause for the breakup of the 
Hosokawa cabinet. 
  Takemura's Sakigake did not send any member to the Hata 
cabinet, but has vowed to back it up from the outside of the 
cabinet until the fiscal 1994 budget passes through the Diet. 

</TEXT>

