<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Leaves for U.S. on `Nuclear Impasse' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ambassador Leaves for U.S. on `Nuclear Impasse' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2105082694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0602 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2105082694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 21 (YONHAP) -- Ambassador for Nuclear 
Affairs Kim Sam-hun on Friday left for Washington to discuss the 
North Korean nuclear impasse. 
  During his stay in Washington for four to five days, Kim is 
scheduled to meet with U.S. Government officials including 
Assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci to evaluate the 
present state of the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  They will focus on joint Korea-U.S countermeasures in view 
of 
the inspection of North Korean nuclear facilities by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  South Korea and the United States will reportedly agree on 
opening a third round of talks between Washington and Pyongyang 
next month if Pyongyang accepts the IAEA's proposal to stop 
refueling the 5-megawatt reactor in Yongbyon and if the spent 
fuel rods that have already been removed are stored in good 
shape. 
  In addition, Seoul and Washington will determine their 
position on subjects to be discussed at the Washington-Pyongyang 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

