<H3> <TI>   IAEA Negotiation Team Arrives in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Negotiation Team Arrives in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2305024894 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0200 GMT 23 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2305024894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Correspondent Yi Tong-sik from Beijing] </F>
  [Text] While additional inspections of North Korea are 
smoothly coming to an end, a working-level negotiation team of 
the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] arrived in Beijing 
this morning. The two-man negotiation team led by Inspections 
Bureau chief (Perry Corse), will leave for Pyongyang at 1520 
tomorrow afternoon [0620 GMT 24 May] via Koryo Airlines after 
staying in Beijing today. While there, the team will conduct 
negotiations with relevant North Korean officials over the 
replacement of nuclear fuel rods. 
  The three inspectors, including chief of Inspections Section 
(Heinonen), who have been watching the replacement of nuclear 
fuel rods while conducting additional inspections in Yongbyon 
after entering North Korea on 19 May, will conclude its 
additional inspections today and leave Pyongyang tomorrow. 
However, the possibility remains that the three-man inspection 
team will present to the working-level negotiation team a report 
on the comprehensive status surrounding the replacement of 
nuclear fuel rods and join the negotiation team. 
  It is expected that the working-level negotiations will 
proceed for at least four to five days this time. There is 
concern, however, that if both sides should stand up to each 
other tensely by sticking only to their previous positions, the 
negotiations will directly stalemate like last August's nuclear 
negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

