<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fisheries Office To Allow Imports of Codfish </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fisheries Office To Allow Imports of Codfish </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2005142094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1133 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2005142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 20 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government has changed a policy and now decided to allow the 
imports of codfish heads as a food, Yi Ui-su, administrator of 
the Fisheries Administration said on Friday. Yi told reporters 
that there no longer is any ground to ban the imports of codfish 
heads. 
  Noting that the United States has consistently been asking 
for their imports, the administrator said, "We have decided to 
permit codfish head imports especially because the United States 
threatens to take a trade retaliation based on Super Article 
301." 
  Yi said that early last March three food hygienic experts 
were sent to the United States to inspect codfish head 
processing. "We have determined there is no problem so far as 
hygienic matters are concerned," he said. 
  Imports of codfish heads, he said, could be made beginning 
some time in the first half of next year at the earliest because 
of the time needed in fixing domestic regulations in both 
countries to facilitate the exports and imports of the item. 
  Thirteen tons and 1,013 tons of American codfish heads were 
imported in 1983 and 1984 before their introduction was halted 
altogether in the face of public uproars that the imports of 
discarded American codfish heads as a food were prone to hurt 
people's health and national prestige. 

</TEXT>

