<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Allows South's Ships To Use Najin Port </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Allows South's Ships To Use Najin Port </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2305022794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0129 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2305022794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 23 (YONHAP) -- Pyongyang prefers Najin in 
the northeastern special economic zone to nearby Chongjin City 
for the proposed direct inter-Korean shipping route to minimize 
North Koreans' exposure to southerners, according to the Korea 
Maritime and Port Administration (KMPA). 
  "Despite the fact that several ships leased by South Korean 
shipping companies have entered Chongjin port, the North Koreans 
insist that South Korean ships use Najin port," KMPA officials 
said Monday. "We think that's a step to prevent the shock of 
opening from spreading to other places by separating the special 
economic area from other regions." 
  Chongjin has an advantage over Najin in terms of railroad 
facilities but suffers a freight vehicle shortage, while Najin 
offers better land transportation with good road conditions, the 
officials quoted ethnic Koreans living in China as saying. 
  Pyongyang seems to have designated Najin as the South-North 
direct trading center in the East Sea, the officials said. 
  Negotiations on the direct shipping route are stalled, 
however, because the North wants the Seoul government not to 
interfere in direct investment by South Korean businesses in the 
development of unloading and transportation facilities at Najin 
port, according to the officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

