<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fishing Boat Captured by PRC Still Being Held </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fishing Boat Captured by PRC Still Being Held </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2305121194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1136 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2305121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Inchon, May 23 (YONHAP) -- Two South Korean fishing 
boats were seized by Chinese patrol boats with their fishermen 
aboard last month for violating the Chinese territorial waters. 
  One of the two has been set free on the condition of 
arranging the payment of a fine. A source at the Inchon Maritime 
Police said on Monday Tongwon-ho No. 61 and Tongwon-ho No. 62, 
both dragnet fishing boats based in Inchon, were seized by the 
Chinese around 3 PM April 16 while they were catching fish 
beyond the Korea-China fishery self-restraint line. 
  The Chinese, while keeping Tongwon-ho. No. 62 as hostage, 
released Tongwon-ho No. 61 on the following day, April 17, with 
the order to arrange the payment of 80,000 U.S. dollars in a 
fine. 
  The owner of the freed ship refused to pay the fine and 
Tongwon-ho No. 62 is still held in captivity in China, the 
source said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

