<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DLP Chairman Expects Social Unrest in June </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DLP Chairman Expects Social Unrest in June </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2305095494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0814 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2305095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 23 (YONHAP) -- Kim Chong-pil, chairman of 
the ruling Democratic Liberal Party, warned Monday of social 
unrest next month, citing such issues as labor-management 
disputes, the outlawed teachers' union and the parliamentary 
probe into the Sangmudae scandal. 
  Speaking at a senior party members' meeting, Kim said, 
"social unrest is expected in June whether we want it or not.... 
labor unions and campuses are restless and the matter of the 
national teachers' union, which vows to rearm itself once it is 
organized, also is uneasy." 
  Moreover, the North Korean nuclear problem poses many 
unanswered questions, although a breakthrough seems to have been 
reached, Kim said. 
  The ruling party chairman demanded that the parliamentary 
investigation into the Sangmudae scandal be concluded in a firm 
and rational way with the party floor leader playing a central 
role, expressing concern that the probe will create an uproar. 
  Kim's remarks were considered a call for the party to 
address 
domestic political issues next month when President Kim 
Young-sam pays a state visit to Russia. 
  The comments, however, also reflected ruling party 
lawmakers' 
view of the current political uneasiness arising from radical 
campus activities and labor unions striving to form a new 
national alliance, experts say. 

</TEXT>

