<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ban on UK Firms, U.S. Trade Policy Contrasted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ban on UK Firms, U.S. Trade Policy Contrasted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2205121794 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 1057 GMT 20 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2205121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Singapore, May 20 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Malaysia's ban 
on British firms from bidding for government contracts cannot be 
compared with American trade policy in Asia, Deputy Prime 
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Friday. He said the Malaysian ban 
was not an attempt to impose its standards and values on the 
British. 
  Malaysia had no choice but to impose the ban because the 
country was made a victim and falsely accused of wrongdoings in 
Anglo-Malaysian trade by the British media, he said. 
  We suffer in every single decision that we made... Every 
contract awarded to the British will create problems for the 
government, for the leaders and the people, he told reporters at 
the airport here before returning to Kuala Lumpur. 
  Anwar was asked whether Malaysia's action against British 
companies could be compared to the United States' policy to link 
trade with human rights issues such as towards China. 

</TEXT>

