<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Ministry on Quarterly Investment Figures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Ministry on Quarterly Investment Figures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2205075794 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0909 GMT 20 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2205075794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, May 20 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- The Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry (MITI) approved 240 projects 
involving an investment of RM [Ringgit Malaysia] 5,838.8 million 
(US$1: RM2.70) in the first four months of this year. 
  Minister Rafidah Aziz said Friday that the figure was an 
improvement on the 231 projects involving RM2,930.3 million for 
the same period last year. 
  Speaking at the launching of Teac's one millionth floppy 
disc 
in Batu Berendam, Melaka, 140 km to the south of here, she said, 
11 projects had investments in excess of RM100 million while 229 
had less than the amount. 
  She said 62 companies were owned by foreigners, 66 by locals 
and 109 were owned jointly, adding that by sector, electronics 
had the largest number of investors both local and foreign with 
63 projects involving RM690.08 million. 
  Rafidah also said that there were five companies nationwide 
producing floppy discs with a total annual output of 19 million 
units. 
  From this figure, 80 per cent was exported to the United 
States, Japan and Korea while the remainder was for local use. 

</TEXT>

