<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Phnom Penh Leaders Support King's Truce Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Phnom Penh Leaders Support King's Truce Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2205132594 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1200 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2205132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1200 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Letter from top leaders of the Royal Government of </F>
Cambodia to His Majesty King Norodom Sihanouk" issued in Phnom 
Penh on 22 May -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] To His Majesty Norodom Sihanouk Varaman, king of 
the Kingdom of Cambodia: 
  Your Majesty, we have received your message dated 22 May 
1994 
concerning the roundtable to be held next week in your 
Chhanghsu-on Palace. 
  Concerning the second and third points in your message, we 
would like to beg permission to inform Your Majesty as follows: 
  A. Concerning the second point, we would like to voice our 
support for your lofty idea on an unconditional, immediate, 
complete, lasting, and irreversible cease-fire over all 
Cambodia. We also support your lofty idea on the monitoring of 
this cease-fire by an inter-Cambodian commission to be made up 
of general and high- ranking military officers from the Khmer 
Royal Armed Forces and the Khmer Rouge group and led by two 
neutral generals representing His Majesty the King of Cambodia. 
  Moreover, we are of the opinion that as a more concrete and 
realistic move, we propose that 13 June 1994 be observed as the 
beginning of the cease-fire. 
  B. Concerning the third point, we would like to voice 
support for your lofty initiative in solemnly declaring our 
eternal allegiance to and support for a unified Cambodia without 
territorial secession [words indistinct] for national peace, 
unity, harmony, and prosperity within the framework of a joint 
endeavor to build the Cambodian nation. 
  We would like also to energetically support your noble idea 
on continuing to make enormous efforts to (?achieve a solution 
to the Cambodian problem). We will arrive in Beijing on 25 May 
to accompany Your Majesty to Chhanghsu-on Palace on 26 May. We 
would like to beg Your Majesty to grant us an audience at your 
residence in Beijing any time at your convenience. 
  May Your Majesty and the Queen enjoy Lord Buddha's blessings 
for longevity, social prestige, happiness, strength, and 
enlightenment. Please forgive any inappropriateness. 
  [Dated] Phnom Penh, 22 May 1994 
  [Signed] Chea Sim, acting head of state and chairman of the 
National Assembly; Norodom Ranariddh, first prime 
minister; Hun Sen, second prime minister 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

