<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Tae-chung Denies Reports on DPRK Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Tae-chung Denies Reports on DPRK Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1905075994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0727 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1905075994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 19 (YONHAP) -- Chairman Kim Tae-chung of 
the Peace Foundation for the Asia-Pacific Region has dismissed 
as "totally groundless" domestic reports that, in an interview 
with THE WASHINGTON TIMES, he said North Korea's possession of 
two or three nuclear weapons would pose no problem. 
  In a statement released through the foundation here Thursday 
[19 May], Kim expressed regret at the incorrect reporting on his 
interview with the U.S. newspaper and asked South Koreans not to 
misunderstand him. 
  "I have persistently said North Korea's nuclear ambitions 
must be completely done away with in tens of lectures, meetings 
and interviews that I have had since my arrival in the United 
States, " he said. 
  THE WASHINGTON TIMES' story contained none of his remarks' 
true meaning, he stressed. 
  On his comments regarding a visit to the United States by 
North Korean President Kim Il-song, he said he had never 
proposed that President Bill Clinton invite Kim to visit 
Washington. "But I have said that I strongly believe Kim's 
participation in a U.N. General Assembly session as the head of 
state of a member nation would have the positive effect of 
solving the North Korean nuclear issue, promoting inter-Korean 
cooperation and easing tension on the Korean peninsula," he 
added. 
  Free discussion of various topics related to national 
unification will help the government forge a unification policy 
on the basis of a national consensus, he said, noting that all 
programs derived from such a policy must be carried out solely 
by the government. 

</TEXT>

