<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Agency Files Complaint Against Goodyear </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Agency Files Complaint Against Goodyear </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1905080094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0732 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1905080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 19 (YONHAP) -- The Fair Trade Commission 
is investigating a Korean sales agency's complaint of unfair 
business practices against the U.S.-based multinational rubber 
and tire firm, Goodyear. 
  The government agency under the Economic Planning Board, 
whose ruling carries binding force, will announce a decision by 
the end of this month. 
  Pusan-based Daeyang Corp. filed a complaint against Goodyear 
Korea last February, charging the American company with ceasing 
to supply goods after the former refused to pay a large 
honorarium and unilaterally breaking off their contract. 
  According to Daeyang's statement, Goodyear Korea demanded 50 
million won for letting the provincial company open sales 
outlets in Pusan and South Kyongsan Province. 
  When it refused, Goodyear stopped supplying products and 
terminated its contract with Daeyang. 
  Goodyear Korea flatly denied Daeyang's charges, saying the 
demand for an honorarium concerned just one of its salesmen who 
has already been sacked over the matter. 
  It explained that Daeyang had failed to submit orders and 
present a business blueprint, a requirement under the contract, 
as reasons for breaking ties. 
  The rights and wrongs will be determined by the Fair Trade 
Commission later in the month, but industry observers say the 
case sends a warning to Korean businesses vying to sell foreign 
brands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

