<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Ministry To Revise Investment Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Ministry To Revise Investment Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2005050194 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 20 May 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> SK2005050194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Finance Minister Hong Chae-hyong said yesterday that 
the government will revise a law governing foreign direct 
investment (FDI) this year to modernize and internationalize 
rules for FDI system. He said the revision of the Foreign 
Capital Inducement Act (FCIA) will be made in this autumn's 
National Assembly session. 
  Through the FCIA revision, the government hopes to eliminate 
or ease rules that hindered the FDI inflow. 
  Many expatriate businessmen have criticized the act for 
being 
too restrictive toward foreign investors. 
  The act, which was passed in 1966, was revised eight times 
in 
the past but has been criticized as being revised piecemeal and 
mostly under foreign pressure. This time, the government seeks 
to rewrite the act "voluntarily" to be more friendly to foreign 
businessmen, a Ministry of Finance official said. 
  The minister acknowledged that despite efforts, Korea could 
not make drastic improvements for foreign businessmen due to 
"domestic- oriented factors." But Korea can no longer delay its 
plan to improve the FDI climate. 
  Minister Hong said Korea should improve its foreign direct 
investment system to levels prevailing in Western OECD 
(Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development) 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

