<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scientists Develop First Satellite Transponder </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scientists Develop First Satellite Transponder </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2005105094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0149 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2005105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 20 (YONHAP) -- A South Korean university 
science team has developed the country's first satellite 
transponder and the world's seventh after such nations as the 
United States, Japan and France. 
  After nearly four years of research and financial aid of 500 
million won from the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry, an 
electronic engineering department team at Kwangun University led 
by Prof. Na Kuk-hwan said Friday it has developed a satellite 
transponder for broadcasting on the tricky Ku frequency band. 
  Industry sources say a Ku-band transponder is designed to 
operate in space for more than 10 years and can be installed in 
a satellite anytime for satellite broadcasting as well as 
communications. 
  "We will be able to install Korean-made transponders in 
satellites and save some 800 million won for every unit in doing 
so," Na said. He said the transponder can be widely applied in 
satellite receivers, ground stations and cellular facilities for 
satellite broadcasting. Na's development will be awarded the top 
prize in the government-sponsored industry-academy-research 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

