<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pacific Basin Economic Council Meets in Malaysia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pacific Basin Economic Council Meets in Malaysia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mahathir Claims Preference for APEC </H4>

<F P=102> BK2305155694 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0643 GMT 23 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2305155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, May 23 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Malaysia 
prefers the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum to 
remain an informal grouping but it will have no choice but to go 
along if other member countries want it to be otherwise, Prime 
Minister Dr. Mahathir Mohamed said Monday. He said if the other 
APEC member countries wanted the grouping to have a permanent 
secretariat and have their leaders meet every year, then 
Malaysia would have to allow itself to be dragged along. 
  Dr. Mahathir was replying to a question during the 
question-and-answer session after delivering a keynote address 
at the 27th International General Meeting of the Pacific Basin 
Economic Council (PBEC) here. He maintained, however, that APEC 
meetings should not be institutionalised. 
  I feel, at this point of time, APEC should be a loose 
organisation so that we can get to know each other better and 
even if the leaders (of APEC countries) want to meet once a 
while, then I think it's o.k., he said. For the time being, the 
leaders should not meet so often (but should instead) leave it 
to the bureaucrats and the ministers to take care of the 
problems; Dr. Mahathir said when the idea of APEC was mooted, 
Malaysia was very concerned that the powerful member countries 
would impose their will on the weak members. APEC, the world's 
biggest regional grouping, links 18 Pacific rim countries 
including North America, Australia and New Zealand. 
  Later, speaking to reporters, Dr. Mahathir said he will 
attend the APEC informal summit in Jakarta in November. 

</TEXT>

