<DOCNO> FBIS4-53816 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas100bb_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pacific Basin Economic Council Meets in Malaysia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pacific Basin Economic Council Meets in Malaysia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SRV Prime Minister Cited on Taiwan </H4>

<F P=102> OW2305083494 Taipei CNA in English 0740 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305083494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Pan Ying-chen and Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, May 23 (CNA) -- Vietnamese Prime 
Minister Vo Van Kiet said here Monday [23 May] he hopes to visit 
Taiwan. 
  "I look forward to visiting Taiwan to see for myself the 
general situation there, but so far I have not received any 
invitation from Taiwan," Vo said after attending the opening 
session of the 27th annual meeting of the Pacific Basin Economic 
Council (PBEC). 
  Many Taiwan officials and business leaders, including 
Economic Affairs Minister P.K. Chiang and Chairman Ting Shan-li 
of the Kuomintang-owned Central Trade and Investment Co., have 
met with Vo in Vietnam during the past year. A number of 
Vietnamese officials, including the head of its Prime Minister's 
Office, have also visited Taiwan in recent years. 
  Despite the absence of diplomatic ties, substantive 
relations 
between Taiwan and Vietnam have grown steadily since the late 
1980s. Taiwan is now Vietnam's largest source of foreign 
capital, with an aggregate direct investment of about U.S.$1.6 
billion. 
  Vo said he hopes Taipei-Hanoi economic cooperation can be 
further strengthened. 
  Vo arrived in Kuala Lumpur Sunday to attend the opening 
ceremony of the May 21-25 annual meeting of the PBEC, a 
non-governmental forum for bankers and business leaders from 
Pacific Basin countries to exchange views and forge cooperative 
ties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

