Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Officials Discuss Political Realignment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Officials Discuss Political Realignment </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    LDP President Yohei Kono </H4>

<F P=102> OW2205143794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2205143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Yohei Kono, president of the Liberal </F>
Democratic Party, by unidentified ASAHI SHIMBUN reporter; place 
and date not given] 
  [Text] [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Diet deliberations on the budget 
for fiscal 1994 have been delayed significantly. How are you 
going to deal with this? 
  [Kono] It is important for us to promote budget 
deliberations. In the past, an administration was always to 
blame for a delay in budget deliberations. This time, however, 
I want the government and the ruling parties to show a sincere 
attitude to the promotion of deliberations. I want to push 
deliberations as much as possible during the 38-day period from 
the start of the Budget Committee session on 23 May until the 
end of Diet session. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Will your party submit a no-confidence 
motion against the cabinet? 
  [Kono] I think we will because this administration does not 
represent the people's will at all and it holds only 40 percent 
of the total seats in the House of Representatives. But, since 
there are several opposition parties, I don't know whether it 
would be good for us to act alone, though there is no doubt that 
we will submit the no-confidence motion. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] When would be the right time to submit the 
motion? 
  [Kono] It is necessary to pass the budget because it is 
related to people's livelihood. Therefore, we must promote 
budget deliberations. But whether or not we will submit the 
motion right after the budget is approved is a different issue 
altogether. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Do you think the Liberal Democratic Party 
[LDP] would win a general election if it was held now? 
  [Kono] I think we would definitely win. We are always ready 
to contest an election. But we want to hold it under the 
single-seat electoral district system, if possible. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Which electoral system--the single-seat or 
the multiseat system--would give the LDP an advantage over other 
parties? 
  [Kono] The single-seat electoral system would give us the 
greatest advantage. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] It is expected that if your party submits a 
no-confidence motion after the bill for redistricting electoral 
constituencies has been submitted to the Diet, the ruling 
parties as well as some LDP members will criticize the party, 
saying it is attempting to "kill political reform." 
  [Kono] The LDP has never said we would force the government 
to dissolve the House of Representatives and hold a general 
election. We only said we cannot trust this cabinet. The 
redistricting bill can be submitted even after the cabinet has 
changed. I rather think some people will start asking if we 
should allow a minority ruling cabinet to redraw the electoral 
districts. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What do you think of the LDP's relationship 
with the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ]? 
  [Kono] Although the LDP is the No. 1 opposition party, we do 
not have a majority. It is natural that the LDP will cooperate 
with several parties if we want to have decisive power. Since 
the LDP and the SDPJ are the major opposition parties, we want 
to cooperate with SDPJ, whenever possible, on Diet matters that 
could result in the overthrow of the current administration. 
But this is possible only if both parties share the same 
perception of the current political situation. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] But there is a large gap between the 
policies of the two parties. Will it become an obstacle to 
cooperation? 
  [Kono] It could become an obstacle. We need further 
discussions within the party as to whether we should start 
policy consultations with the SDPJ immediately. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] How about the LDP's relationship with 
Shinto Sakigake [Harbinger Party]? 
  [Kono] I think that psychologically, the SDPJ and Sakigake 
have something in common. But as far as policies are concerned, 
there are more similarities between Sakigake and the LDP. Since 
Sakigake is saying it will "not join the cabinet but support the 
coalition until the budget is approved," we may not share with 
Sakigake as many views as we do with the SDPJ in dealing with 
Diet matters during budget deliberations. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Do you think Sakigake could be a partner in 
coordinating policies? 
  [Kono] I think so. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Since you have been giving priority to the 
issue of avoiding another split within the party, there is a 
criticism both inside and outside the LDP that you have failed 
to drastically reform the party. 
  [Kono] I think there is a big difference between the current 
LDP and the old LDP, which had Mr. Ichiro Ozawa (Shinseito 
secretary general) and other people as its members. Mr. Ozawa 
used to shut himself up in the office of secretary general with 
people who are now Shinseito members. My LDP is entirely 
different. Mr. Michio Watanabe once said we needed a "reform 
tantamount to forming the party." I think he is right. But I 
also think we have done a good job in revising the seniority 
system, in which certain favors were given to party members 
depending on how many terms they served in the Diet and which 
factions they belonged to. Though I would not say the revision 
was done perfectly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

