<H3> <TI>   Steel Firms Enter Agreements With U.S. Firms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Steel Firms Enter Agreements With U.S. Firms </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Aichi Steel-Louisville Forge Ties </H4>

<F P=102> 942A0216B Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Apr 94 p 
10--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0216B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] (Nagoya) Aichi Steel Works signed a consulting 
contract concerning the construction of a factory with U.S. 
forged steel products maker Louisville Forge and Gear Works of 
Kentucky. Aichi Steel Works will advise Louisville Forge on the 
layout, equipment specifications, and final manufacturing 
processes for a new forging plant which the latter plans to 
build. President J. Payton of Louisville Forge visited Japan on 
5 April to sign the contract. 
  Louisville Forge supplies the three major automakers and 
Japanese automakers with North American plants with forged 
components. Louisville Forge has maintained a technical 
assistance agreement with Aichi Steel Works since July 1990 and 
in August of last year it had reached a technical assistance 
agreement on the manufacture of crankshafts using "nontempered 
steel" which does not involve heat processing. Louisville Forge 
is formulating plans for relocation and construction of a new 
plant, but the timing and location are still undetermined. 

</TEXT>

