<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Fuel Plant Makes Plutonium Disclosure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Fuel Plant Makes Plutonium Disclosure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205144994 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 May 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2205144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 20 May, Power Reactor and Nuclear Fuel 
Development Corporation (Donen) publicly disclosed for the first 
time that a large amount of plutonium had adhered to equipment. 
  As much as 70 kilograms of plutonium stuck to equipment at 
Donen's plutonium fuel plant (located in Tokaimura, Ibaraki 
Prefecture). 
  There are 17 airtight containers, called glove boxes, in the 
fuel plant. To prevent possible radiation contamination, 
operators wear rubber globes and operate the equipment installed 
in the containers while standing outside. 
  Plutonium adhesion occurred inside the glove boxes. Blackish 
plutonium reportedly could be seen stuck to pipes and other 
equipment. Of the 17 containers, large amounts of the 
plutonium, 60 percent of the total amount, was accumulated in 
two containers containing equipment to harden powder plutonium 
into fuel pellets, and another container which contains machines 
to grind the pellets to a unified, standard size. 
  Currently the container which contains the largest amount of 
adhered plutonium is not in use. However, because of strong 
radiation, observers studied the containers through a thick 
glass wall. As a result of this, no plutonium inside the 
containers was visible to the naked eye. 
  The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) asked the fuel 
plant to reduce the amount of adhered plutonium. Measurement 
error is within plus or minus 10 percent and 70 kilograms of 
plutonium is involved in this case. Therefore nobody would 
notice even if enough plutonium to produce an atomic bomb was 
missing. Many other countries are concerned about the case and 
foreign media from nine countries sent representatives to see 
the containers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

