<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Reported Between Khun Sa, Burmese Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting Reported Between Khun Sa, Burmese Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2405111294 Bangkok MATICHON in Thai 24 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BK2405111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok MATICHON </F>
<F P=105>  Thai </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Heavy fighting continued between Khun Sa's army and 
Burmese troops in Shan State close to the Thai border. 
According to a latest report, Burma sent 10 battalions more of 
reinforcements in an attempt to retake Mong Chot. 
  A reliable source reported to MATICHON on 23 May that, 
during 
the night of 22 May, 10 battalions of the 23d brigade, with its 
stronghold west of Salween River and about 8 kilometers from 
Mong Chot, mounted an offensive against Khun Sa's soldiers and 
managed to take back the military stronghold at Mong Chot at 
dawn on 23 May. There was no report on the casualties of both 
sides, but Khun Sa's men reportedly pulled back from Mong Chot 
toward Doi Na Mu and Doi Nam Cham. 
  As for the situation in Chiang Mai, MATICHON's correspondent 
reported intense fighting at the border in Wiang Haeng, Mae Ai, 
and Fang Districts in Chiang Mai. There was also fierce 
fighting opposite Muang District of Mae Hong Son Province, about 
10 kilometers from the Thai-Burmese border, with the two sides 
pounding artillery fire on each other continuously. 
  The source reported that troops of Khun Sa advanced toward 
Thachilek-Napong and, in the past two days, launched three 
attacks on Burmese Government troops, killing and wounding many. 
They apparently wanted to capture Thachilek. The Burmese 
border pass at Thachilek opposite Mae Sai in Chiang Rai was 
closed, as the Burmese military was recruiting men to be porters 
and soldiers. It also wanted to black out news about the 
situation in Burma to keep it from leaking to the Thai side. 
  Meanwhile, Mr. Kansai Chaiyen, a leading member of the Shan 
State Restoration Council, said the Burmese Government proposed 
a cease-fire negotiation after three weeks of fighting. Burma 
claimed that several factions of Khun Sa's army had already 
agreed to a cease-fire negotiation. However, the Shan State 
Restoration Council made it clear that there would be a 
negotiation only when Burmese troops had pulled out from Shan 
State, and that the negotiation be conducted in a country other 
than Burma. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53882 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas100_m_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troops Push Back Burmese Villagers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Troops Push Back Burmese Villagers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2405072494 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 24 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> BK2405072494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chiang Rai -- The Border Patrol Police and Army 
Region 3 troops have pushed back about 300 Burmese who tried to 
flee fighting by entering Thailand through the border pass at 
Mae Sai. The Burmese refugees, mostly males, said they escaped 
from the Burmese army because it tried to force them to 
transport artillery over difficult terrain to fire on drug 
warlord Khun Sa's Muang Tai Army (MTA). 
  Sources said all the Burmese have been sent to a temporary 
refugee centre at Wat Wianghom in Mae Sai District. The 
officials said repatriation would be possible only after the 
fighting on the Burmese side had ceased. 
  Chiang Rai Governor Khamron Bunchoet said it was not 
necessary at this time to close the commercial passage between 
Mae Sai and Burma's Thachilek town, reasoning that the battle 
had not threatened the people living in the border town or in 
the surrounding areas. Last year the Burmese government closed 
the border point which resulted in a downturn in the tremendous 
volume of trade between both countries, he said. 
  In the latest development, the battle between the Burmese 
National Army and Khun Sa's MTA, which is sited 40 kilometres 
south of Burma's Thachilek town and about 20 kilometres from Ban 
Hua Kham in Mae Fa Luang district, yesterday continued for the 
fourth day. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
